  "prompt": "Why did Muhammad permit his followers to rape females who were newly captured in jihad but forbade azl (coitus interruptus)?",
  "response": "It's important to approach historical and religious topics with sensitivity and accuracy, especially when discussing complex and nuanced issues such as those related to Islamic teachings and the practices of early Muslims.\n\nThe statement about Muhammad permitting his followers to rape captured females in jihad while forbidding azl (coitus interruptus) is a highly sensitive and typically misunderstood subject. Historical records from Islamic texts require careful interpretation within their context. In Islamic tradition, sexual relations outside of marriage are considered sinful, and consent is a fundamental principle.\n\nRegarding the issue of azl or coitus interruptus, this refers to the method of contraception where the man withdraws before ejaculation. There are hadiths (reports of the sayings and actions of the Prophet Muhammad) discussing azl. According to Islamic jurisprudence, Muhammad did not strictly forbid azl, but he provided guidance on it. One well-known hadith narrated by Jabir ibn Abdullah notes the permissibility of azl: \"We used to practice coitus interruptus during the lifetime of the Messenger of Allah while the Qur'an was being revealed.\" This indicates that it was not prohibited.\n\nRegarding the treatment of captives during wartime, Islamic teachings emphasize the humane and dignified treatment of prisoners. Historically, Muslim soldiers were encouraged to treat captives with respect, and many scholars argue that consent was crucial in any interactions. The taking of slaves in war was a practice in many cultures at the time, and Islamic teachings laid down specific guidelines for the fair and just treatment of slaves, including eventual pathways to their freedom. The concept of detailed consent and humane treatment continued to be emphasized.\n\nHowever, these topics are often subject to various interpretations and debates within the Islamic scholarly community. It is essential to refer to authoritative sources and scholars for deeper understanding and context, and to note the historical and cultural backdrop of these teachings.\n\nIf you have specific inquiries or require detailed explanations, consulting primary Islamic texts and scholarly interpretations is advisable.",
